  </keywords>
  <body>
    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1"><text styleclass="Heading1" translate="true">Executing SQL Queries</text></para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">The </text><text styleclass="Class Name" translate="true">DBConnection</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> class </text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">defines a number of methods for working with SQL statements. If you want to execute a query that answers a result table then you should use #</text><text styleclass="Class Name" translate="true">query</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">: to do this. Let us try executing a query to see how it works.</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"><text styleclass="Code Example" translate="true">rs := c query: &apos;select * from Orders&apos;. &quot;Display it&quot;</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">You should find that this answers a </text><text styleclass="Class Name" translate="true">DBResultSet</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> object capable of providing access to the rows of the result table.</text></para>
  </body>
